**NoUI --- DERP POC**

Project Knowledge Analysis & Client Questionnaire

February 21, 2026 --- Comprehensive Cross-Document Review

**Executive Summary**

This document presents the results of a comprehensive analysis of all
NoUI project knowledge documents, including 14 domain knowledge
documents (doc01--doc14), DERP-published forms and flyers (Retirement
Application, Spousal Consent forms, DRO forms, Health Insurance forms,
member flyers), case calculation files, test fixtures, architecture
references, process definitions, and build history. The analysis
cross-references every claim, formula, rate, and process definition to
identify conflicts, ambiguities, and gaps that must be resolved before
(or during) POC development.

The review found that the CRITICAL-001 discrepancy (early retirement
reduction rates) has been properly identified and resolved across
project files. However, several additional issues remain that require
client clarification to ensure the POC accurately reflects DERP's actual
operational practices.

**Section 1: Previously Identified & Resolved Conflicts**

These issues were discovered in earlier work sessions and have been
corrected in project documents. They are listed here for completeness
and to confirm resolution status.

**1.1 CRITICAL-001: Early Retirement Reduction Rates (RESOLVED)**

**Issue:** Original documents stated 6% per year for all tiers. DERP
sources confirm 3% for Tiers 1 & 2, 6% for Tier 3 only.

**Status:** RESOLVED. All project files corrected. Case 2 recalculated
(\$1,633.07 vs prior \$933.18). CLAUDE.md, test fixtures, system prompt,
and build history updated.

**Residual:** RMC §18-401(c) direct text verification still pending.
Probability of error in three independent DERP sources is effectively
zero, but statutory confirmation would be ideal.

**1.2 CRITICAL-002: Employer Contribution Rate (RESOLVED)**

**Issue:** Project documents stated 11%. DERP Handbook (Jan 2024) states
17.95%.

**Status:** RESOLVED. Decision 26 updated rate. Seed data generator
should use era-appropriate rates.

**Residual:** Historical contribution rate schedule needed for accurate
synthetic data generation across employment eras.

**1.3 IMPORTANT-001: Social Security Make-Up Benefit (RESOLVED --- Out
of Scope)**

**Status:** Decision 25 explicitly marks this as OUT OF SCOPE for POC.
Placeholder rule RULE-SS-MAKEUP added. Application intake still collects
SS Estimate for Tier 1/2 age 62+.

**1.4 IMPORTANT-002: Lump-Sum Death Benefit (RESOLVED --- In Scope)**

**Status:** Decision 23 added to POC scope. Rules, calculations, and
workspace components defined.

**Section 2: Newly Identified Conflicts & Discrepancies**

The following issues emerged from cross-referencing the complete
document set and require attention.

**2.1 Lump-Sum Death Benefit --- Disability Retirement Formula**

**Source:** Retirement Application (Part C, Revised 06/10/2025)

The retirement application reveals a disability retirement death benefit
formula not captured in project documents: for Disability Retirement
before age 65, the benefit is 150% of the member's annualized AMS,
limited to \$50,000. This benefit is reduced to \$5,000 at age 65. While
disability retirement is out of POC scope, this formula exists on the
actual application form members will see.

**Impact:** LOW for POC (disability is out of scope), but the rules
engine should have a placeholder acknowledging this formula exists.

**2.2 Pop-Up Provision --- Confirmed but Not Modeled**

**Source:** Retirement Application (Part B) and Doc06 (Payment Options)

The DERP Retirement Application (Part B) explicitly states: "I
understand that if my beneficiary should predecease me, I may not select
another beneficiary. However my benefit will be increased prospectively
to the Type 1, Maximum Benefit." Doc06 flags this as "verify whether
DERP offers pop-up provisions." The application form confirms DERP does
offer pop-ups.

**Impact:** MEDIUM. The POC should acknowledge pop-up in the payment
option explanation, even if post-retirement pop-up processing is out of
scope. The retirement application language should be reflected in
workspace design.

**2.3 DRO Agreement Form --- DROP/DROP II Division**

**Source:** DRO_Agreement.pdf (DERP form)

The DERP DRO Agreement form includes provisions for dividing Deferred
Retirement Option Plan (DROP/DROP II) accounts in addition to the
defined benefit plan. Our project documents mention DRO division of the
pension benefit but do not reference DROP at all. DROP is a separate
program where members who are eligible to retire but continue working
can accumulate benefits in a lump-sum account.

**Impact:** LOW for POC (DROP is not in scope), but this reveals an
entire benefit program (DROP and DROP II) that exists at DERP and is not
documented in our project knowledge.

**2.4 Spousal Consent --- Two Distinct Forms**

**Source:** SpousalConsentBeforeRetirement.pdf and
SpousalConsentAtRetirement.pdf

DERP uses two separate spousal consent forms with different legal
implications. The "Before Retirement" form is revocable and applies to
active/inactive members. The "At Retirement" form is irrevocable,
permanent, and cannot be signed more than 90 days before the first
payment. Our project documents reference spousal consent as a single
concept without distinguishing these two forms or their timing
constraints.

**Impact:** MEDIUM. The workspace must distinguish which form applies
and enforce the 90-day timing constraint for the At Retirement form.

**2.5 Lump-Sum Death Benefit --- Reduction Formula Discrepancy**

**Source:** Retirement Application Part C vs. IMPORTANT-002 in process
definition

The process definition's IMPORTANT-002 states the early retirement death
benefit is "\$2,500 at age 55, reduced by \$250 per year under 65."
However, the retirement application form states: "the lump-sum death
benefit is reduced by \$250 for each year the member is under the age of
65" starting from \$5,000, not \$2,500. The CRITICAL-001-resolution.md
file correctly interprets this as \$5,000 minus (\$250 × years under
65), yielding \$2,500 at age 55. The discrepancy is in the process
definition's description, not the calculation itself.

**Impact:** LOW. The calculations are correct; only the descriptive
language needs cleanup.

**2.6 BUILD_PLAN.md Still References 6% Reduction**

**Source:** BUILD_PLAN.md, Step 2.4

The BUILD_PLAN.md file still contains "Early retirement reduction: 6%
per year under age 65" in the benefit calculation rules section. While
the CLAUDE.md, test fixtures, and case calculations have all been
corrected, this planning document was not updated.

**Impact:** LOW. Risk of confusion if someone reads BUILD_PLAN.md
without checking BUILD_HISTORY.md Decision 22.

**2.7 50% J&S Factor Inconsistency in Case 4**

**Source:** BUILD_HISTORY.md Decision 17 vs. Case 4 Calculation

Decision 17 standardized J&S factors including 50% J&S at 0.9450.
However, the Case 4 DRO calculation uses 0.9350 for the 50% J&S option.
This creates a small discrepancy in the illustrative payment option
amounts.

**Impact:** LOW. These are placeholder factors anyway, but they should
be internally consistent across all demo cases.

**2.8 Doc05 AMS Values --- Illustrative vs. Actual**

**Source:** doc05-benefit-calculations.docx vs. case calculation files

Doc05 uses illustrative AMS values (e.g., \$10,433.33 for Case 1,
\$7,346.00 for Case 2, \$8,500.00 for Case 3) while the case calculation
files use precise values derived from synthetic salary histories
(\$10,639.45 for Case 1, \$7,347.62 for Case 2). This is expected since
doc05 was written as a training document, but it means doc05 will
produce different final benefit amounts than the test fixtures.

**Impact:** LOW. Expected divergence, but doc05 should note that values
are illustrative and test fixtures contain authoritative calculations.

**2.9 Retirement Application --- Re-Employment Rules**

**Source:** Retirement Application Part H

The application confirms the 30-day separation minimum and 1,000-hour
annual limit for re-employment with covered employers. Violation results
in benefit suspension for the remainder of the calendar year. Our
project docs reference this but do not detail the enforcement mechanism
or how the system should track it.

**Impact:** LOW for POC. Re-employment monitoring is a post-retirement
function outside initial scope, but the rules should be documented.

**Section 3: Vague or Undefined Areas Requiring Clarification**

These are areas where our project documentation makes assumptions, uses
placeholder values, or where DERP's actual operational practices are not
fully captured.

**3.1 Actuarial Factors for J&S Options**

All demo cases use placeholder actuarial factors (Decision 19). DERP
must have published actuarial factor tables that vary by member age,
beneficiary age, and J&S percentage. Without these, payment option
amounts are illustrative only. We need DERP's actual factor tables or
the methodology to derive them.

**3.2 Rounding Methodology**

Doc05 discusses rounding options (standard, banker's, truncation) and
recommends verifying against plan documents. BUILD_HISTORY Decision 21
specifies banker's rounding for the POC, but this has not been verified
against DERP's actual practice.

**3.3 Service Credit Calculation Precision**

Robert Martinez's service is calculated as 28.75 years using 9/12
months, but the exact duration is 28 years, 9 months, 17 days (28.797
years by exact day method). The case files use the year-month method
rounding to the nearest quarter. DERP's actual service credit
calculation methodology (exact days, year-month, or hours) is
unconfirmed.

**3.4 Leave Payout --- PTO vs. Sick/Vacation**

Case 2 notes Jennifer Kim was hired before Jan 1, 2010 (eligible for
leave payout) but has PTO rather than separate sick/vacation leave. The
case assumes PTO is not eligible. DERP's actual rules on PTO eligibility
for pension calculation purposes are unclear.

**3.5 Interest Rate on Contribution Refunds**

The project documents state non-vested members receive contributions
plus interest but do not specify the interest rate, compounding method,
or crediting frequency DERP uses.

**3.6 Anti-Spiking Provisions**

Doc03 discusses anti-spiking rules that limit AMS manipulation through
late-career salary spikes. Whether DERP has specific anti-spiking
provisions (e.g., a cap on year-over-year salary increases in the AMS
window) is not documented.

**3.7 Service Purchase Cost Methodology**

Doc08 discusses various cost calculation methodologies (actuarial
present value, employee contribution based, full actuarial cost) but
does not specify which method DERP uses or what the current cost factors
are.

**3.8 Deferred Retirement Eligibility Age**

Our documents note deferred retirement as a category but do not specify
at what age a deferred-vested member can begin collecting benefits under
DERP rules.

**3.9 COLA History and Application Method**

COLAs at DERP are discretionary and board-approved. We don't have the
historical COLA schedule, how COLAs are applied (compounding on current
benefit vs. fixed on original), the effective date pattern, or whether
there's a waiting period before new retirees receive their first COLA.

**3.10 Health Insurance Plan Details for IPR**

The IPR benefit is conditional on enrolling in a DERP group health plan.
The Health Insurance Election Form shows specific plan options (Kaiser,
UnitedHealthCare, Humana, Cigna, Delta, VSP). The workspace should
display available plans, but we need to know if plan eligibility varies
by any member attribute.

**3.11 MyDERP Self-Service Portal**

The Retirement Application references a "MSS Portal" and "MyDERP.org"
for self-service. Understanding what members can already do through this
portal is important for understanding how NoUI fits alongside existing
member self-service capabilities.

**3.12 Tax Withholding Rules**

The Retirement Application (Part E/F) captures federal and Colorado
state tax withholding elections. The workspace needs to present these
options, but the specific withholding calculation rules and defaults are
not documented.

